        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Advanced: Using IIFE for Inline Complexity"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Immediately-invoked function expressions (IIFEs) allow you to use "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "if"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "/"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "switch"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " directly inside JSX when you need multi-branch logic inline. This is rarely needed — a helper function is usually clearer — but it is sometimes useful for one-off complex logic:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "function Chart({ type, data }) {\n  return (\n    <div className=\"chart-wrapper\">\n      {(() => {\n        switch (type) {\n          case 'bar': return <BarChart data={data} />;\n          case 'line': return <LineChart data={data} />;\n          case 'pie': return <PieChart data={data} />;\n          default: return <p>Unknown chart type: {type}</p>;\n        }\n      })()}\n    </div>\n  );\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The IIFE executes immediately and its return value is the JSX child. Most style guides discourage this pattern in favour of extracting a named function, but it is valid React."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Conditional Class Names and Styles"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Conditionals are also common in attribute values, especially "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "className"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " and "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "style"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ":"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// Conditional className\nfunction Button({ isActive, isDisabled, children }) {\n  const classes = [\n    'btn',\n    isActive && 'btn-active',\n    isDisabled && 'btn-disabled'\n  ].filter(Boolean).join(' ');\n\n  return (\n    <button className={classes} disabled={isDisabled}>\n      {children}\n    </button>\n  );\n}\n\n// With a classnames library (common pattern)\nimport cx from 'classnames';\nfunction Button({ isActive, isDisabled, children }) {\n  return (\n    <button\n      className={cx('btn', { 'btn-active': isActive, 'btn-disabled': isDisabled })}\n      disabled={isDisabled}\n    >\n      {children}\n    </button>\n  );\n}\n\n// Conditional inline styles\nfunction Highlight({ isSelected, children }) {\n  return (\n    <span\n      style={{\n        backgroundColor: isSelected ? '#fef3c7' : 'transparent',\n        fontWeight: isSelected ? 700 : 400,\n      }}\n    >\n      {children}\n    </span>\n  );\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Summary"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "JSX only accepts expressions, so "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "if"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " and "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "for"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " statements must live outside the JSX tree. The four idiomatic patterns are: ternary for A/B choice, "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "&&"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " for show-or-nothing (with care around the 0 gotcha), "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "if"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "/"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "else"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " before the return for guard clauses and complex branching, and helper functions for reusable or switch-like logic. Choose the simplest pattern that is readable for the number of branches involved. Be aware that swapping component types in a conditional causes unmount/remount — sometimes intentional, sometimes a state-loss bug."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "Key takeaways: "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "JSX accepts expressions, not statements. Ternary for A/B, && for show-or-nothing (avoid with raw numbers — use count > 0), if/else outside JSX for 3+ states or guard clauses. false/null/undefined render nothing; 0 renders as text. Switching element types at the same position resets state. CSS display:none preserves state; removing from JSX does not."
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
}
